<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOOD SAMARITAN'S CONDITION 'STABLE' AS HIS NEIGHBORS RAISE FUNDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BLAKE FONTENAY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While the man police call a good Samaritan lay in a hospital bed fighting for 
his life Thursday, his wife described him as someone who often helped people in 
need without fear for his own safety. 
</P>
<P>
"He just cares about people," Sandra Smith said of her husband, Gary, a 
part-time carpet layer and paralegal. "He doesn't want to see people get hurt." 
</P>
<P>
Gary Smith was shot four times after he responded to a University City woman's 
screams for help by chasing a man who had just burglarized the woman's home. 
</P>
<P>
Gary Smith was laying carpet in a building next to the woman's home in the 7900 
block of Camino Tranquilo when he heard screams and confronted a gun-wielding 
man about a block away, police said. 
</P>
<P>
Doctors at Scripps Memorial Hospital in La Jolla operated on Gary Smith several 
times Thursday, treating bullet wounds in his face, stomach, left leg and left 
arm, hospital officials said. 
</P>
<P>
"He is in stable condition," hospital spokeswoman Dilene Pulsipher said late 
Thursday afternoon after one of the operations. 
</P>
<P>
Smith's encounter with the burglar wasn't his first attempt at helping a crime 
victim, his wife told reporters. Last Sunday, the 35-year-old San Diegan, who 
aspires to become a corporate lawyer, unsuccessfully gave chase to a purse 
snatcher, she said. 
</P>
<P>
Gary Smith never stopped to think that he might get hurt while aiding others, 
his wife said. Now others in the community are taking steps to help him. 
</P>
<P>
Members of the San Diego Police Officers Assn. announced Thursday that they 
will donate blood to Smith. 
</P>
<P>
"It's an emotional issue for us, too," said police Officer Robert Chorny, who 
attended a press conference with Sandra Smith at the hospital. "We've basically 
dubbed this guy 'the good Samaritan.' " 
</P>
<P>
Residents of the neighborhood where the shooting occurred are raising funds for 
Smith's medical expenses. 
</P>
<P>
"They are going to make a private donation," Pulsipher said. "They wanted to do 
it away from the media." 
</P>
<P>
Hospital officials requested that anyone wishing to donate money to the Smiths 
write to: Foundation for Gary Smith, Scripps Memorial Hospital, P.O. Box 28, La 
Jolla, CA, 92038. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police are still looking for a suspect in the case. Chorny said 
investigators have several leads, including a report that someone had tried to 
use one of the credit cards stolen during the burglary. 
</P>
<P>
Witnesses described the assailant as a young white man, about 5-foot-9 and 140 
pounds, with a light complexion and long, thin, brown hair. The man, described 
as clean-shaven but with an unkempt appearance, was last seen wearing a gray or 
blue Windbreaker and a pair of old jeans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
