<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIRING CENTER IS LURING WORKERS BUT ONLY A HANDFUL OF EMPLOYERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AARON CURTISS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Men seeking work continue to crowd the city's first hiring center for day 
laborers in the San Fernando Valley, but employers apparently have yet to 
discover the dusty North Hollywood lot on Sherman Way between Radford and Hinds 
avenues. 
</P>
<P>
About 100 men have been gathering each morning at the center, opened last week 
on a Department of Water and Power lot a few blocks west of Lankershim 
Boulevard. But only about five prospective employers show up on an average day, 
said Bill Molina, management analyst for the Community Development Department, 
which runs the center. 
</P>
<P>
At a dedication ceremony Tuesday, city officials and others who helped organize 
the center encouraged employers to hire workers from the site rather than the 
street corners and parking lots where many day laborers still congregate. 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles City Councilman Ernani Bernardi, whose district includes the 
center, said the facility provides a "responsible place" for men to wait for 
work. 
</P>
<P>
"This benefits the entire community, not just the people who come here looking 
for work," Bernardi said. "We want to make this an overwhelming success so we 
can expand it into other areas of the Valley." 
</P>
<P>
Bert Corona, executive director of Hermandad Mexicana Nacional, an immigrant 
rights group that helped organize the center, said the site is "humanizing the 
effort for those who hunger for work." 
</P>
<P>
While they wait for work, men at the center are offered free coffee, pastries 
and English lessons. Picnic tables and portable toilets have been set up at the 
site. 
</P>
<P>
The center is intended to serve the 150 to 200 laborers who congregate on 
Lankershim between Strathern and Saticoy streets and reduce problems caused by 
loitering workers. Funded by the city, the facility costs about $3,500 a month 
to operate. 
</P>
<P>
It is the second such gathering place for workers in the city of Los Angeles. A 
similar facility was opened in Harbor City last fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, A laborer watches the activities during Tuesday's formal opening day at 
the hiring center. CARLOS CHAVEZ / Los Angeles Times; Photo, Men seeking work 
listen to speakers at dedication ceremonies at the North Hollywood hiring 
center. ; Photo, Group of mariachis provides music at opening ceremonies. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
