<HEADLINE>
<P>
BUILDER IN TORRANCE FEUD FILES FOR BANKRUPTCY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Deborah Schoch 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A developer who has been feuding with the city of Torrance said this week that 
Park Beyond the Park, an investment group with which he is connected, has been 
forced to file for bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
The developer, Jerry L. Conrow, criticized the city for blocking the group's 
efforts to rent space to the Los Angeles County court system in a building the 
group developed. 
</P>
<P>
"They basically didn't want the court system to expand within Torrance, so they 
set requirements that no one could meet," said Conrow, who is general partner 
of Park Beyond the Park. Specifically, he cited a city requirement that one 
parking space be provided for every 150 square feet of floor space in any 
building used for court purposes. 
</P>
<P>
Park Beyond the Park, described by Conrow as a partnership of about 25 people, 
owns a 126,000-square-foot office building at 1880 S. Crenshaw Blvd. 
</P>
<P>
The group filed a lawsuit in January claiming that the city cost it the court 
contract. A second lawsuit by Conrow, which challenged the city's review of 
parking for its cultural arts center, was dismissed in Superior Court last 
month. 
</P>
<P>
Jeff Gibson, senior principal planner for the city, declined to comment on 
Conrow's criticisms because of the pending litigation. 
</P>
<P>
Conrow said the group filed for protection under Chapter 11 of the Federal 
Bankruptcy Act on July 12. Deborah Schoch 
</P>
</TEXT>
