<HEADLINE>
<P>
IT'S NOT HAPPY TRAILS FOR BIKERS; 
</P>
<P>
ECOLOGY: MOUNTAIN BIKES HAVE BEEN BANNED FROM THE SENSITIVE UPPER NEWPORT BAY 
PRESERVE UNTIL SPECIFIC TRAILS CAN BE DESIGNATED FOR THEIR USE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LAURA MICHAELIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEWPORT BEACH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On a recent Saturday, county Park Ranger Nancy Bruland pointed to the dusty 
bluffs rising above her in the Upper Newport Bay. Along with the established 
hiking path winding horizontally up the hill, there was a number of deep, bumpy 
ruts cutting their way down the ridge. 
</P>
<P>
The ruts were largely made by mountain bikers and have been additionally eroded 
by more bikers, hikers and the natural water runoff in the area. Since Bruland 
took the job as sole county caretaker of the 115-acre Upper Newport Bay 
regional park, which lies to the west of Jamboree Road and north of Back Bay 
Drive, she has seen between five and seven mountain bikers each day on the 
paths. Some of them, she said, are simply unconcerned about the damage that 
they can do to park hills and the animal environments. 
</P>
<P>
"Erosion is the biggest concern. When they blaze new trails, they wipe out the 
vegetation," Bruland explained, adding that since she went to work at the park 
late last year, several residents have told her how the number of bikers has 
increased steadily over the last couple of years. 
</P>
<P>
So, until specific trails are designated for mountain bike riders by the 
county's General Park Development Plan, Bruland is prohibiting bicycles from 
the park, leaving them the asphalt paths at road level for their racing and 
riding. 
</P>
<P>
Bruland is not the first to accuse some Orange County cyclists of riding 
roughshod over the environment. Last fall, complaints from South Laguna 
residents prompted county officials to abandon plans to run a bike path through 
part of Aliso Canyon. And in Orange, bike riders were blamed for scaring horses 
being ridden down a bridle path along the Santa Ana River. 
</P>
<P>
Skip Lauderbaugh, a spokesman for the biking club, SHARE, expressed frustration 
at the Newport Bay limitations, though he said he sympathizes with Bruland's 
concern. 
</P>
<P>
"I've lived down the street from the Back Bay for 30 years, and I've been 
hiking back there since I was 6 years old," Lauderbaugh said. "Instead of 
restricting access, they need to educate the people as to how sensitive an 
environment it is." 
</P>
<P>
Lauderbaugh maintains that people have been breaking new trails for as long as 
he has lived near the park and says that since people come from all over the 
county to the few parks that are open to mountain bikers, the trails that 
remain open will have to tolerate a greater number of users. 
</P>
<P>
But he and other members of SHARE agree that there has to be a greater 
awareness of the environment among mountain bikers. The group has produced an 
educational pamphlet instructing riders on biking etiquette, on the safe ways 
to bike and the need to stay on the trail. Their group takes the stance that 
all trail users in the park need to cooperate to keep the park safe for animals 
and plants that live there. 
</P>
<P>
Bruland is not just concerned about erosion and crushed vegetation but also 
</P>
<P>
possible damage to the habitats of the burrowing owl and the light-footed 
clapper rail. The clapper rail, a relatively uncommon bird, makes its nest in 
the short brush of the west-bluff side of the park. Upper Newport Bay is the 
home to about 70% of the birds. 
</P>
<P>
"There's a lot of kids on BMX bikes, and they're cutting new trails and causing 
erosion, and there's no doubt about it," said SHARE member Marcko Popovich, 
but, he added, conscientious riders do not break new paths, speed or hog the 
trails. In fact, Lauderbaugh added, "we're more critical of people riding that 
way than others . . . and 90% of the riders are really safe people." 
</P>
<P>
Lauderbaugh and Bruland agree that there has to be a recognized policy for 
bikers and other trail users in the Upper Bay, where for years hikers, 
horseback riders and cyclists have shared the road and paths. They, along with 
other residents of the area and naturalists, are working to plan a safe course 
for the park through the county's General Development Plan. 
</P>
<P>
Part of the plan also needs to spell out enforcement of trail restrictions, 
Bruland added. Despite vigilant patrols, and help from Fish and Game rangers 
and local residents, some bike riders ignore the signs posted at entrances to 
the facility. And once they are caught, Bruland doesn't have the authority to 
issue citations -- though she can have the riders removed from the park by 
police. In most cases, she said, she tries to explain to the riders the harm 
that they can do to the park. 
</P>
<P>
"It depends on how you approach them. . . . Sometimes they'll listen and pay 
attention and sometimes they tell you to, frankly, mind your own business," she 
said. "I have found that it's a real me-type of generation around here." 
</P>
<P>
Though the blame does not entirely fall on the shoulders of mountain bikers, 
Bruland feels that until a policy can be worked out that balances the need of 
the bikers with the protection of the resources, no bikes should be allowed on 
the dirt paths inside the park. Popovich agrees, though he hopes that with 
speed limits and additional education for cyclists using the park, sufficient 
trails can be maintained. 
</P>
<P>
And SHARE also sponsors a program that helps revegetate land that has been 
eroded by human activities by planting native plants and by shoring up eroding 
bluffs. Members of the group have spoken with Bruland and are making plans for 
future projects in the Bay area. 
</P>
<P>
The County Board of Supervisors is tentatively scheduled to approve the 
temporary ban, along with a number of other interim park provisions, during its 
Aug. 7 meeting. The General Development Plan for the park is due out within the 
next two years, county officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, County Park Ranger Nancy Bruland walks on one of the Upper Bay trails 
close to University Avenue. ; Photo, COLOR, Perched near a trail in Upper 
Newport Bay is county Park Ranger Nancy Bruland, virtually the sole protector 
of the park. MARK BOSTER / Los Angeles Times; Photo, COLOR, Mountain bike 
tracks, a sign of endangerment to the fragile Upper Bay. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
