<HEADLINE>
<P>
3 OFFERS MADE TO FORD FOR ITS SUBSIDIARY; 
</P>
<P>
DEFENSE INDUSTRY: HUGHES AIRCRAFT IS ONE OF THE BIDDERS FOR FORD AEROSPACE 
CORP., WHICH EMPLOYS 17,000 PEOPLE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEWPORT BEACH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ford Motor Co. said Thursday that it has received three offers for its Ford 
Aerospace Corp. defense subsidiary, including one from Hughes Aircraft Co. in 
El Segundo. 
</P>
<P>
Ford spokesman Tom Rhoades in Dearborn, Mich., declined to disclose the bid 
prices, but sources have estimated the going price may be about $600 million. 
</P>
<P>
The company said it expects to select the final bidder by next week. 
</P>
<P>
Rhoades said one of the three bids was a joint offer from Hughes Aircraft Co. 
in El Segundo and Alcatel Co. of France. Sources say that Alcatel wants to buy 
Ford's commercial satellite business, while Hughes wants the subsidiary's 
defense businesses. 
</P>
<P>
Hughes spokesman Richard Dore said the company will neither confirm nor deny 
its involvement in any potential acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
The other bids were from Loral Corp., a New York defense electronics company, 
and a team of companies including Westinghouse Electric Corp., the investment 
firm Carlyle Group, and Aerospatiale of France, which is connected with the 
Airbus aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
Loral spokeswoman Elizabeth Allen confirmed that the company had submitted a 
bid but declined to disclose details or say when she expected a decision from 
Ford. 
</P>
<P>
Ford Motor put its Newport Beach-based Ford Aerospace unit up for sale on Jan. 
12, saying it wanted to focus on its automotive operations. Analysts originally 
estimated that the company would draw bids of more than $1 billion, but sources 
say the depressed state of the defense industry led to lower bids. 
</P>
<P>
Ford Aerospace has revenue of about $2 billion a year, two thirds of it from 
the defense sector. The company employs 17,000 people, including more than 
3,000 at its Aeroneutronic division in Newport Beach. 
</P>
<P>
The company's products and operations include the Sidewinder air-to-air 
missile, space communications satellites and support work for NASA in Houston. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
ACQUISITIONS; FORD AEROSPACE &amp; COMMUNICATIONS CORP; HUGHES AIRCRAFT CO; 
ALCATEL NV; LORAL CORP; WESTINGHOUSE ELECTRIC CORP; CARLYLE GROUP LP; 
AEROSPATIALE 
</P>
