<HEADLINE>
<P>
NAMES IN THE NEWS; 
</P>
<P>
NOW WHAT'S THAT NAME AGAIN? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ST. LOUIS PARK, Minn. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The annual meeting of the national Jim Smith Society came to order today and it 
was time to share stories about what it means to be a Jim Smith. Often, it 
means inconvenience. 
</P>
<P>
About 50 Jim Smiths had registered for the gathering, which will include the 
Jim Smith golf tournament, the all-Jim Smith softball game, "Meet Jim Smith" 
mixers and JIMGO, a version of bingo. 
</P>
<P>
"I've met about 300 Jim Smiths at these conventions over the years and I can 
honestly say I never met a Jim Smith I didn't like," said Jim Smith of Camp 
Hill, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
The society was founded in 1969 and has 1,533 members worldwide. The Jim Smiths 
at the annual meeting can commiserate about the headaches they share because of 
their name. 
</P>
<P>
"When I bought my house, I had to sign affidavits saying that I was not the Jim 
Smith that was sentenced to 15 to 20 years in prison," said founder Jim Smith 
of Dayton, Ohio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
