<HEADLINE>
<P>
ARCHER-DANIELS TO BUY PFIZER CITRIC ACID UNIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pfizer Inc. said it has reached an agreement to sell the company's citric acid 
business to Archer-Daniels-Midland Co. 
</P>
<P>
Terms were not disclosed, but Pfizer said the divestiture will yield "a profit" 
for the company. 
</P>
<P>
Pfizer's sales of citric acid, a key chemical component in the food beverage 
and pharmaceutical industries, amounted to more than $180 million in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
Pfizer's main citric acid production sites are in Southport, N.C., and 
Ringaskiddy, Ireland, and have 700 employees. 
</P>
<P>
The health-care and specialty chemicals company said it would retain its 
Groton, Conn., citric acid plant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
